# One component per file

Every React component must be defined in its own file.

## Rules

- One default or named component export per `.tsx` file (small local helpers like formatters are fine if they are not components).
- Do not add multiple component functions (e.g. `function Foo()` and `function Bar()`) in the same file.
- File name should match the component name in PascalCase (e.g. `DistributionChart.tsx` exports `DistributionChart`).
- When splitting a file, colocate shared types/constants in a sibling file only if reused by multiple components (e.g. `chartColors.ts`, `types.ts`).

## Examples

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — multiple components in one file
function SingleYearDistributionChart() { ... }
function SingleYearMonthlyBreakdownChart() { ... }
export default function SingleYearCharts() { ... }

// ✅ GOOD — one file per component
// src/components/single-year-charts/SingleYearDistributionChart.tsx
export default function SingleYearDistributionChart() { ... }

// src/components/single-year-charts/SingleYearCharts.tsx
import SingleYearDistributionChart from './SingleYearDistributionChart';
export default function SingleYearCharts() { ... }
```

When editing a file that already violates this rule, prefer extracting new components into separate files rather than adding more components to the same file.
